commentPreTextItems.html: All West Indies hopes on these two men. Can they do it?

commentTextItems.html: caught at cover! No they can't. It was a flighted delivery on the off stump and Narine drives it in the air towards the off side and Tamim Iqbal flies full stretch and plucks this catch from nowhere. What a ripper!

commentPostTextItems.html: So that's all from our side. Thanks for all your feedback and comments. This is Devashish Fuloria signing off for now. Ciao ciao.

Presentation: Mushfiqur Rahim: "Boys really played well, especially Anamul and everyone took the responsibility. It is a great challenge and opportunity for the young guys in the team to use and develop. Anamul's innings was fantastic and held one end together. Mominul was also good as he got us quick runs. The bowlers really played well especially Sohag Gazi. West Indies are a dangerous side and they will come back hard on us, so we need to be ready for Dhaka."

Darren Sammy: "Bangladesh outplayed us in both these games. Both the bowling and the batting are areas of concern. We need to dig deeper if we have to come back from behind in this series. We have the guys in the team to do that  and I back them to do that."
Anamul Haque is the Man-of-the-Match for his maiden century.

Bangladesh complete their biggest win in ODI cricket. Their previous best was the 146-run win over Scotland, but that record has been shattered by some margin here. West Indies were chasing a big total here and their batting imploded extraordinarily. The damage was again done by the spinners - Gazi and Razzak taking three wickets apiece. But what was alarming was the complete lack of resistance from the World T20 champions. Bangladesh have taken a 2-0 lead now and on current form they look good to win this series.
"I suppose this puts Anamul's sluggish innings in perspective," says Nahim.
Rahman: "With Tamim catching like that, who needs him to bat?"

Asif: "@Gav: I completely disagree about going backwards. We have ONLY improved. Overseas wins, Asia cup performances are proofs of that. And the World Cup wasn't exactly bad. we could do with a bit of luck, which we didn't have. All I am saying is that we are not "ordinary". Not anymore."

commentPostTextItems.html: Only one more to for Bangladesh to complete a comprehensive win

dismissalText.commentary: Darren Bravo c †Mushfiqur Rahim b Abdur Razzak 28 (41b 3x4 0x6 69m) SR: 68.29

dismissalComment.html: caught behind! And another one bites the dust. It was flighted outside off and the batsman came forward to defend, but he played down the wrong line as he expected the ball to turn into him. The ball went on straight and took the edge. Mush juggled it a bit but caught it comfortably

dismissalComment.html: caught behind! He bowls this one flat and fast outside off and Marlon Samuels went back to punch it through off side, but gets a faint edge to the keeper.

headshotImage.longCaption: Abdur Razzak player page headshot cutout, 2021

dismissalText.commentary: Dwayne Smith lbw b Abdur Razzak 0 (3b 0x4 0x6 7m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: not this time, it is exactly similar delivery and Smith plays down the wrong line as he comes forward in defence. This time the gap between the bat and the pad was big enough to quell doubts. That would have hit the middle stump. But looks like that there was an inside edge. So Smith is unlucky as it appeared plumb to the naked eye

milestones.description: Mushfiqur and Anamul Haque's 174-run partnership is BAN's highest for the 3rd wicket in ODIs, breaking the record of 141 between Ashraful and Raqibul Hasan
Bangladesh's 161-run win against West Indies is the largest margin of victory in terms of runs in ODIs, beating 146-run win against Scotland

recentReportStory.title: Bangladesh thrash West Indies to record biggest win
recentReportStory.subTitle: Bangladesh v West Indies, 2nd ODI, Khulna
recentReportStory.seoTitle: Bangladesh annihilate West Indies to record biggest win
recentReportStory.summary: Bangladesh recorded their biggest even win in ODIs in terms of runs, thrashing a listless West Indies by 160 runs to take a 2-0 lead and put a foot in the door in claiming the five-match series

image.caption: Anamul Haque became the third Bangladesh teenager to score a ODI century
image.longCaption: Anamul Haque became the third Bangladesh teenager to score a ODI century, Bangladesh v West Indies, 2nd ODI, Khulna, December 2, 2012

recentReportStory.credit: Kanishkaa Balachandran is a senior sub-editor at ESPNcricinfo
